  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Money laundering laws and approaches vary across different countries, but I'll provide an overview of some key comparative legal approaches:\n\n1. United States Approach:\n- Comprehensive Bank Secrecy Act and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations\n- Strict reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Aggressive criminal prosecution\n- Focus on international cooperation and information sharing\n\n2. European Union Approach:\n- Unified Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Centralized regulatory framework\n- Emphasis on customer due diligence\n- Harmonized legal standards across member states\n\n3. United Kingdom:\n- Proceeds of Crime Act\n- Enhanced financial intelligence capabilities\n- Strong emphasis on international collaboration\n- Sophisticated asset recovery mechanisms\n\n4. Switzerland:\n- Historically more lenient banking secrecy laws\n- Gradually increasing transparency\n- Sophisticated financial monitoring systems\n- Cooperative international stance in recent years\n\n5. China:\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict governmental oversight\n- Increasing alignment with international standards\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Key Comparative Elements:\n- Varying definitions of predicate offenses\n- Different reporting thresholds\n- Varying levels of financial institution obligations\n- Distinct enforcement mechanisms\n\nThese approaches reflect different legal, cultural, and economic contexts.",
